# Feature Specifications & Use Cases
## Early Emotional Distress Detection & Support App

---

## Overview

This document provides detailed specifications for all 9 core features of the Early Emotional Distress Detection & Support App. Each feature is designed with user safety, privacy, and emotional well-being as top priorities.

---

## Feature 1: Daily Mood & Emotional Check-In

### Purpose
Enable early detection of emotional distress by tracking daily mood patterns and identifying concerning trends before they escalate to crisis.

### User Benefit
- Develop self-awareness of emotional patterns
- Identify triggers and stressors
- Receive early intervention when distress patterns emerge

### Functional Requirements

#### FR1.1: Daily Check-In Prompt
- **Trigger:** Push notification at user-selected time (default: 9 PM)
- **Frequency:** Once daily
- **Dismissible:** Yes, but tracked as "skipped"
- **Customization:** User can change notification time

#### FR1.2: Mood Assessment Questions

**Question Set:**
1. **Overall Mood:** "How are you feeling today?"
   - 😊 Great
   - 🙂 Good
   - 😐 Okay
   - 😞 Not good
   - 😢 Terrible

2. **Stress Level:** "How stressed are you today?"
   - Scale: 1 (Not stressed) to 5 (Extremely stressed)

3. **Work Impact:** "Did work or workload affect you today?"
   - Yes, significantly
   - Yes, somewhat
   - No, not really
   - I didn't work today

4. **Family Impact:** "Did family pressure affect you today?"
   - Yes, significantly
   - Yes, somewhat
   - No, not really

5. **Optional Open Response:** "Anything you want to note about today?"
   - Free text (max 500 characters)

#### FR1.3: Response Time
- **Target:** Complete check-in in < 2 minutes
- **Design:** Simple, visual, minimal typing

#### FR1.4: Data Storage
- All responses stored locally and encrypted
- Synced to cloud with end-to-end encryption
- Retention: Indefinite (user can delete)

### User Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Notification: Daily Check-In] --> B{User Opens App}
    B -->|Yes| C[Mood Selection Screen]
    B -->|Dismissed| D[Mark as Skipped]
    C --> E[Stress Level Scale]
    E --> F[Work Impact Question]
    F --> G[Family Impact Question]
    G --> H[Optional Note]
    H --> I[Submit]
    I --> J{Mood Analysis}
    J -->|Concerning Pattern| K[Show Support Resources]
    J -->|Normal| L[Show Encouragement]
    K --> M[Save Data]
    L --> M
    M --> N[Return to Home]
```

### Early Detection Logic

#### Alert Triggers:
1. **Severe Mood (3+ consecutive days):**
   - Mood: 😞 or 😢 for 3+ days
   - Action: Suggest breathing exercise, peer support

2. **High Stress (5+ consecutive days):**
   - Stress level: 4-5 for 5+ days
   - Action: Burnout warning, self-care suggestions

3. **Crisis Indicators:**
   - Mood: 😢 + Stress: 5 + Open response contains crisis keywords
   - Action: Immediate crisis intervention screen

### Privacy Considerations
- Data never shared without explicit consent
- No employer or family access
- Anonymized for trend analysis only

### Safety Mechanisms
- Crisis keyword detection in open responses
- Immediate intervention for severe patterns
- Professional help suggestions

---

## Feature 2: Workload Stress Tracker

### Purpose
Help users recognize unhealthy work patterns and burnout risk by tracking working hours, deadlines, and overtime.

### User Benefit
- Visualize workload trends
- Recognize burnout before it becomes severe
- Evidence-based conversations with managers about workload

### Functional Requirements

#### FR2.1: Work Hours Logging

**Input Methods:**
1. **Manual Entry:** User logs start/end times
2. **Quick Log:** "Worked late today" (adds 2 extra hours)
3. **Calendar Integration:** Optional sync with Google/Outlook calendar

**Data Captured:**
- Work start time
- Work end time
- Break duration
- Weekend work (yes/no)
- On-call status (yes/no)

#### FR2.2: Deadline Tracking
- User can log upcoming deadlines
- Deadline pressure rating (1-5)
- Automatic reminder 3 days before deadline

#### FR2.3: Overtime Calculation
- Automatic calculation of hours beyond 40/week
- Weekly overtime summary
- Monthly overtime trends

#### FR2.4: Burnout Risk Assessment

**Burnout Indicators:**
| Indicator | Threshold | Risk Level |
|-----------|-----------|------------|
| Weekly hours | 50-60 hours | Medium |
| Weekly hours | 60+ hours | High |
| Consecutive weekend work | 2+ weekends | Medium |
| Consecutive weekend work | 4+ weekends | High |
| Overtime trend | Increasing 3+ weeks | Medium |
| Combined high stress + high hours | Both present | High |

### User Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Open Workload Tracker] --> B[View Weekly Summary]
    B --> C{Log Today's Hours?}
    C -->|Yes| D[Enter Start/End Time]
    C -->|No| E[View Trends]
    D --> F[Log Breaks]
    F --> G[Weekend Work?]
    G --> H[Calculate Total Hours]
    H --> I{Burnout Risk?}
    I -->|High Risk| J[Burnout Alert]
    I -->|Normal| K[Save Data]
    J --> L[Show Coping Resources]
    L --> K
    K --> M[Update Dashboard]
```

### Visualizations

1. **Weekly Bar Chart:** Hours worked per day
2. **Monthly Trend Line:** Average weekly hours over time
3. **Overtime Heatmap:** Visual representation of overtime frequency
4. **Burnout Risk Gauge:** Visual indicator (green/yellow/red)

### Burnout Alert

**When Triggered:**
- High-risk burnout indicators present

**Alert Message:**
> ⚠️ **Burnout Alert**
> 
> You've worked 65+ hours for 3 consecutive weeks. This pattern increases risk of burnout.
> 
> **Suggested Actions:**
> - Take a mental health day
> - Talk to your manager about workload
> - Practice self-care this weekend
> - Connect with peer support

### Privacy Considerations
- Work data never shared with employers
- User controls all data sharing
- Can export data for personal use

---

## Feature 3: Family Pressure Assessment

### Purpose
Validate and normalize feelings related to family expectations, comparisons, and pressure through reflective assessments and journaling.

### User Benefit
- Recognize that family pressure is a legitimate stressor
- Process emotions in a safe, private space
- Identify patterns and triggers
- Reduce shame and guilt

### Functional Requirements

#### FR3.1: Weekly Assessment

**Frequency:** Once per week (user-selected day)

**Assessment Questions:**
1. "This week, did you feel pressure to meet family expectations?"
   - Not at all
   - A little
   - Moderately
   - Quite a bit
   - Extremely

2. "Did family comparisons (to siblings, cousins, friends) affect your self-worth?"
   - Not at all
   - A little
   - Moderately
   - Quite a bit
   - Extremely

3. "Did you feel guilty about your career or life choices?"
   - Not at all
   - A little
   - Moderately
   - Quite a bit
   - Extremely

4. "Did you suppress your feelings to avoid disappointing family?"
   - Not at all
   - A little
   - Moderately
   - Quite a bit
   - Extremely

5. "Rate your overall family-related stress this week:"
   - Scale: 1 (No stress) to 5 (Extreme stress)

#### FR3.2: Emotional Journaling

**Purpose:** Safe space to express suppressed emotions

**Features:**
- Private, encrypted journal entries
- Optional prompts:
  - "What family expectation bothered you most this week?"
  - "How did comparisons make you feel?"
  - "What do YOU want, separate from family expectations?"
  - "What would you say to your family if there were no consequences?"

**Privacy:**
- Completely private (not shared with AI or community)
- User can delete entries anytime
- Optional: Share anonymously in peer support

#### FR3.3: Validation Responses

**After Assessment Completion:**

If high family pressure detected:
> 💙 **Your Feelings Are Valid**
> 
> Family pressure is real and affects many early-career individuals. You are not weak for feeling this way.
> 
> **Remember:**
> - Your worth is not determined by family approval
> - It's okay to have different goals than your family expects
> - Setting boundaries is healthy, not selfish
> 
> **Suggested Resources:**
> - Read peer stories about family pressure
> - Journal about your authentic desires
> - Practice boundary-setting techniques

### User Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Weekly Reminder: Family Assessment] --> B[Open Assessment]
    B --> C[Answer 5 Questions]
    C --> D{High Pressure Detected?}
    D -->|Yes| E[Validation Message]
    D -->|No| F[Encouragement Message]
    E --> G[Suggest Journaling]
    F --> G
    G --> H{User Wants to Journal?}
    H -->|Yes| I[Open Journal with Prompts]
    H -->|No| J[Save Assessment]
    I --> K[Write Entry]
    K --> J
    J --> L[Update Trends]
```

### Trend Analysis

**Tracked Over Time:**
- Family pressure score trends
- Guilt levels
- Suppression patterns
- Correlation with overall mood

**Insights Provided:**
- "Your family pressure has increased over the past month"
- "You've felt guilty 8 out of 12 weeks"
- "Family stress correlates with your low mood days"

### Safety Mechanisms
- Detect severe emotional distress in journal entries
- Suggest professional help if patterns worsen
- Crisis intervention if suicidal ideation expressed

